#1 Resected stage IIA (T3, M0, N0) colon cancer
Dr. Robin English was diagnosed to have a transverse colon lesion based on an abdominal CT-scan.  He had a colonoscopy that revealed a mass in the transverse colon that was biopsy-proven to be an invasive, poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma.  On June 21, 2010, he underwent an extended right hemicolectomy with a side-to-side ileotransverse anastomosis.  The pathology revealed a 5-cm ulcerated mass that was found to invade through muscularis into the pericolic fat.  There was no angiolymphatic invasion, surgical margins were negative, and 14 dissected lymph nodes were free from metastatic disease.  Dr. English has a stage IIA resected colon cancer.  There is no role for adjuvant chemotherapy in this setting.  Dr. English can return to the GI Clinic for regular surveillance and follow-up.
#2 Urothelial neoplasm
Dr. English was incidentally noted to have a urothelial malignancy involving the left bladder wall, extending into the bladder neck.  This has resulted in a left-sided ureteric obstruction with a left-sided hydronephrosis.  Dr. English was offered a TURBT versus a cystectomy during his colon surgery, but preferred not to choose either of the options.  Dr. English will need to return to the Southeast Louisiana State Medical Office for further follow-up and management.
Thank-you for the consult.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

